But in any exchange, a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing the anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key hit is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is due to the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched on computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that supplementary line.
This is a phase of file sharing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital score.
Computers "cook" the new transaction and add a number before "trash" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular mark (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any change would change the trace.
If, in order to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge is 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculation power.
