A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever with regard to the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, he decided to play everything.
He welcomed everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given that Assembly two more months to finish his work.
And almost two years ago Egypt used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial turmoil.
This new initiative has only increased the country's fracture.
For his opponents, the president continued in his "autocratic delirium" and continued "traiting his word" and "scattering the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote my text or keep the full powers," powers which are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its vast majority, voted yesterday.
Most Liberals did not come to the call.
By mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they considered that they could not make their point of view.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, seconded members, were added to all the haste yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As I expected, the articles voted have been unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, for the fact that one of the few differences in the day had been expressed almost at the time of prayer, so many members of the committee had come to think that the Constitution clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all views, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulates that "the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of the law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "standards", which would have allowed a more strict application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals hold him out of hypocrisy and consider him to be nothing more than an advert.
According to them, Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular to anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia's laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the preeminences of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next director of that university would be much less moderate than the present one.
"For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have been working on this text are not illiterate but academics, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms employed imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, etc.].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent the civil judges are competent to pronounce themselves above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday received many criticisms relating to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers will claim to be few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the Defence Budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Civil proceedings in military courts, as requested by human rights associations, will also not be prohibited.
They also showed concern about the text, which they consider to be libertarian.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially those of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underscoring Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive was the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word was not found in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president had to go out on television last night, events were scheduled for this afternoon.
