Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member of the ESA of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began to work closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission during the following years.
However, Poland’s journey to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already dedicated to flying to space before the Second World War, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw astronomical observatory where, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the indifferent assistants and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch award in France for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a major promoter of astronomy and cosmonautism.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautism, he was known worldwide and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a train was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and it is not known the project's disadvantages either.
It is not clear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the dress or for its braking.
Information on this dress is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to be dedicated to the missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Arms in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawe Wolfkem and Prof. Gustave Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation has reached the stage of practical evidence.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937, the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study was published "Rakieta - torpeda poietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautische Society (Polish Towarzystow Astronautique).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, for the first time reference is made to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronauts.
In one of them, Professor Subotowice proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) had longed to be a member of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimier Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautic Federation.
He performed this duty until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Meteorological Rakeita), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apex of 1,800 metres, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and two-stage RM-2 rockets were launched in the Błūdów desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket averaged 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was going to be the object of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a 14.5 km apex and its mission would be to control the wind at the height.
However, the work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was Meteor-1, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) developed, which differed from each other by the space available to scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum landing in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In the context of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the Space Space Research on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
