It is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by taking the sulfur out of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To this end, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphurous gas that flows from the inside of the Earth is solidified by contact with the air.
After starting out large sulphur rocks, which come to a total of about 70 kilos, they are carried in two bamboo baskets that load on their shoulders through paved stone paths.
They are only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters high, but the worn-out carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb the tortoise, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to get back and fall through the precipitation.
They know that any miscarriage could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who spent years at the risk of Kawah Ijen.
